		<p class="preamble">Being a pretty big fan of many winter sports I have spent most evenings of the past two weeks in front of the TV, watching the action from the Vancouver 2010 Winter Olympics.</p>
<p>With excellent live TV coverage from the games I had no reason to visit either the <a href="http://vancouver2010.com/">Vancouver2010.com</a> or the <a href="http://ctvolympics.ca/">CTVOlympics.ca</a> website to find more info about the games. But one person who <strong>has</strong> visited and taken a closer look at those sites is Joe Clark. What he found is that the <a href="http://joeclark.org/access/webaccess/vancouver2010/">Vancouver Olympics Web sites are inaccessible to disabled people</a>.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.456bereastreet.com/archive/201003/accessibility_issues_on_vancouver_olympics_websites/">Read full post</a></p>
<p>Posted in <a href="http://www.456bereastreet.com/archive/categories/accessibility/" rel="tag">Accessibility</a>, <a href="http://www.456bereastreet.com/archive/categories/web_standards/" rel="tag">Web Standards</a>.</p>
