	";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:4:"name";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Golgotha";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}}}}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:65:"<div lang="en" dir="ltr">Using jQuery with ASP.NET Controls</div>";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:5:"xhtml";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"rel";s:9:"alternate";s:4:"type";s:9:"text/html";s:4:"href";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/search-this/~3/_WsFRAcMGj4/";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8884:"<div>
		<p>jQuery, a lightweight (only 19kb in size) JavaScript library has become my new best friend. It&#039;s like mushrooms to Mario. Obviously I&#039;m not alone since Microsoft is now distributing jQuery with Visual Studio (including jQuery intellisense). If you are using the new MVC framework from Microsoft then you will no doubt become familiar with the intricate workings of jQuery.</p>
<p>jQuery is not all that difficult to learn. The biggest thing you have to understand is all the different &quot;<a href="http://docs.jquery.com/Selectors">selectors</a>&quot; that are available to you. Using <a href="http://docs.jquery.com/Selectors">selectors</a> developers can query, in a CSS like way, for HTML elements, and then apply &quot;commands&quot; to them.</p>
<p>For example, the below JavaScript uses jQuery to find a &lt;div&gt; element within a page that has a CSS id of &quot;rightSide&quot;, and shows it and &quot;leftSide&quot; and hides it.</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="ljavascript-27"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('javascript-27'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">JAVASCRIPT:</span>
<div class="javascript" id="javascript-27">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4">$<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;div#rightSide&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>.<span class="c3">show</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
<li class="c6">
<div class="c4">$<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;div#leftSide&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>.<span class="c3">hide</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>As another example, the JavaScript below uses jQuery to find a specific &lt;table&gt; on the page with an id of &quot;datagrid1&quot;, then retrieves every other &lt;tr&gt; row within the datagrid, and sets those &lt;tr&gt; elements to have a CSS class of &quot;even&quot; - which could be used to alternate the background color of each row:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="ljavascript-28"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('javascript-28'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">JAVASCRIPT:</span>
<div class="javascript" id="javascript-28">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4">$<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;#datagrid1 tr:nth-child(even)&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>.<span class="c3">addClass</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;even&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>This next example gets all links &lt;a&gt; in a specific &lt;div&gt; and attaches an onclick event to them:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="ljavascript-29"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('javascript-29'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">JAVASCRIPT:</span>
<div class="javascript" id="javascript-29">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4">$<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;#navBtns a&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>.<span class="c3">bind</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;click&#039;</span>, <span class="c7">function</span><span class="c1">(</span>event<span class="c1">)</span><span class="c1">{</span></div>
</li>
<li class="c6">
<div class="c4">     event.<span class="c3">preventDefault</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c1">)</span>; <span class="c8">//stop the link from going to href</span></div>
</li>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4">     <span class="c8">//do something</span></div>
</li>
<li class="c6">
<div class="c4"><span class="c1">}</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>Being able to traverse the DOM and locate HTML elements to attach events, behaviors, animations and CSS is priceless. But what about ASP.NET controls like the RadioButtonList, GridView, ListView, Repeater, and many others that we as developers like to bind to? How do we traverse them when they all get their ids auto-generated? That&#039;s what we will look at now! And with jQuery it&#039;s not that hard!</p>
<p>When you add an ASP.NET RadioButtonList control to a page, like below:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="lcsharp-30"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('csharp-30'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">C#:</span>
<div class="csharp" id="csharp-30">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4">&lt;asp:RadioButtonList runat=<span class="c9">&quot;server&quot;</span> ID=<span class="c9">&quot;rblCaseControl&quot;</span> /&gt;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>The browser renders the control to the code below:</p>
<p><img src="http://www.search-this.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/08/radioButtonListScreenshot.png" alt="radioButtonList screenshot" title="radioButtonListScreenshot" width="896" height="290" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-883"></p>
<p>As you can see, we don&#039;t have control over the generated items id tag. It would not be an easy task to guess what the auto-generated id tags are going to be. There&#039;s simply too many ways it can very depending on if you are using master-pages and or web-controls. The one thing that we do know is that somewhere in the id will be the id we gave to the control; in this case &quot;rblCaseControl&quot;. Lucky for us this is all jQuery needs to go to town. Look at the code below:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="ljavascript-31"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('javascript-31'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">JAVASCRIPT:</span>
<div class="javascript" id="javascript-31">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4"><span class="c7">var</span> rblCaseControl = $<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;input[type=radio][id*=rblCaseControl]&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>This code uses jQuery to get all radio buttons that have &quot;rblCaseControl&quot; somewhere in their id tag. We could get the selected value of the radio button list using this code:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="ljavascript-32"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('javascript-32'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">JAVASCRIPT:</span>
<div class="javascript" id="javascript-32">
<ol>
<li class="c5">
<div class="c4"><span class="c7">var</span> rblCaseControl = $<span class="c1">(</span><span class="c2">&#039;input[type=radio][id*=rblCaseControl]:checked&#039;</span><span class="c1">)</span>.<span class="c3">val</span><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c1">)</span>;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>With this code we have now found the selected value from our ASP.NET RadioButtonList control using jQuery. Perhaps now we want to send that value to a web method in our codebind page using Ajax? Well we could use jQuery for that too! But, that&#039;s another article.</p>
