<h2>The Setup</h2>
<p>Add the <strong>System.Net.Mail</strong> namespace. The System.Net.Mail namespace contains everything we need to send email using a Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) server for delivery.</p>
<p>Modify the <strong>Web.config</strong> file to include the below:</p>
<div class="igBar"><span id="lcode-52"><a href="http://www.search-this.com" onclick="javascript:showPlainTxt('code-52'); return false;">PLAIN TEXT</a></span></div>
<div class="syntax_hilite"><span class="langName">CODE:</span>
<div class="code" id="code-52">
<ol>
<li class="c3">
<div class="c2">&lt;system.<span>net</span>&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c4">
<div class="c2">    &lt;mailSettings&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c3">
<div class="c2">      &lt;smtp from=<span class="c12">&quot;admin@company.com&quot;</span>&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c4">
<div class="c2">        &lt;network host=<span class="c12">&quot;localhost&quot;</span> port=<span class="c12">&quot;25&quot;</span>  /&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c3">
<div class="c2">      &lt;/smtp&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c4">
<div class="c2">    &lt;/mailSettings&gt;</div>
</li>
<li class="c3">
<div class="c2">  &lt;/system.<span>net</span>&gt;</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
<p>The kicker and not well documented part to note is the from=&quot;admin@company.com&quot; in the smtp tag. You can change the from address later, but the <strong>MailDefinition</strong> class needs this here.</p>
<p>That&#039;s it for setup. Now let&#039;s look at the first chunk of code.</p>
